<exercise checkit-seed="0004" checkit-slug="SQ5" checkit-title="Basic convergence tests">
    <statement>
        <p>
            For each of the following series, use the <em>Divergence</em>, <em>Alternating Summation</em> or <em>Integral</em> test to determine if the series converges.
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{3 \, n^{4} + 3 \, n^{3} + 4}{2 \, n^{4} + 5 \, n^{3} + 1}.</m>
            </li>            
            <li>
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{n^{\frac{1}{4}}}.</m>
            </li>            
            <li>
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{\left(-1\right)^{n}}{2 \, n}.</m>
            </li>            
        </ol>
    </statement>
    <answer>
       <ol>
            <li>
                
                        <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{3 \, n^{4} + 3 \, n^{3} + 4}{2 \, n^{4} + 5 \, n^{3} + 1}</m> diverges by the <em>Divergence</em> test.               
                   
                
            </li>            
            <li>
                
                        <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{n^{\frac{1}{4}}}</m> diverges by the <em>Integral</em> test.               
                   
                
            </li>            
            <li>
                
                        <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{\left(-1\right)^{n}}{2 \, n}</m> converges by the <em>Alternating Summation</em> test.                
                   
                
            </li>            
        </ol>
    </answer>
</exercise>
